# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
"""Places batch C: Jodhpur (Blue City) & Jaisalmer (Golden City)."""
POSTS = []
def P(**k): POSTS.append(k)

# ---- JODHPUR ----

P(slug="mehrangarh-fort-jodhpur", city="Jodhpur", region="Marwar", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Mehrangarh Fort", query="Mehrangarh Fort Jodhpur",
  excerpt="One of India's grandest forts, rising 120 metres of sheer rock above Jodhpur's sea of blue houses.",
  tags=["fort","Jodhpur","icon","museum"],
  info=dict(timings="9 AM – 5 PM (daily)", entry="Approx ₹100 (Indian) / ₹600 (foreign, incl. audio guide)",
            best="Morning; late afternoon for the blue-city views", duration="2–3 hours", reach="Atop the hill in the centre of Jodhpur; steep walk or short drive up"),
  body="""<p>Few forts in the world make an entrance like Mehrangarh. Rising 120 metres of unbroken cliff above the blue houses of Jodhpur, its ramparts seem carved from the very rock. Founded in 1459, it remains one of the largest and most magnificent forts in India — and one of the best preserved.</p>
<p>Within its walls, a superb museum occupies a series of exquisitely decorated palaces — the Moti Mahal, Phool Mahal and Sheesh Mahal — filled with palanquins, arms, paintings and royal treasures. From the ramparts, the view over the indigo-washed old city is unforgettable.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The view over Jodhpur's blue houses from the ramparts.</li><li>The opulent Phool Mahal and Sheesh Mahal palaces.</li><li>The excellent audio guide, included with foreign tickets.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The audio tour is genuinely one of the best in India — use it. There's a zip-line circuit for the adventurous. Sunset over the blue city from here is spectacular.</p>""")

P(slug="umaid-bhawan-palace-jodhpur", city="Jodhpur", region="Marwar", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Umaid Bhawan Palace", query="Umaid Bhawan Palace Jodhpur",
  excerpt="One of the world's largest private residences — a golden-stone Art Deco palace that's part royal home, part luxury hotel, part museum.",
  tags=["palace","Jodhpur","Art Deco","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="Museum 9 AM – 5 PM (palace & hotel are private)", entry="Museum approx ₹30 (Indian) / ₹100 (foreign)",
            best="Morning", duration="1 hour (museum)", reach="Chittar Hill, ~5 km from the old city"),
  body="""<p>Completed in 1943, Umaid Bhawan is one of the largest private residences on earth — a vast palace of golden-yellow sandstone that fuses Rajput grandeur with sleek Art Deco style. It's divided into three parts: the royal family's private residence, a legendary luxury hotel, and a museum open to visitors.</p>
<p>Built partly as a famine-relief project to employ thousands during a drought, the palace is a monument to both ambition and compassion. The museum showcases the era's glamour — vintage cars, clocks, and the story of its remarkable construction.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The sweeping Art Deco architecture and manicured grounds.</li><li>The vintage car collection in the museum.</li><li>The grand central dome, visible across the city.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Only the museum section is open to non-guests; the palace and hotel are private. It's a quick but atmospheric visit — pair it with Mehrangarh and Jaswant Thada.</p>""")

P(slug="jaswant-thada-jodhpur", city="Jodhpur", region="Marwar", cat="Heritage Site",
  name="Jaswant Thada", query="Jaswant Thada Jodhpur",
  excerpt="The 'Taj Mahal of Marwar' — a serene royal cenotaph of luminous white marble beside a lake, below Mehrangarh.",
  tags=["Jodhpur","marble","memorial","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="9 AM – 5 PM (daily)", entry="Approx ₹30 (Indian) / ₹50 (foreign)",
            best="Morning, combined with Mehrangarh", duration="45 minutes", reach="Just below Mehrangarh Fort — a short walk or drive"),
  body="""<p>A short distance from Mehrangarh, the Jaswant Thada is a jewel of a memorial — a royal cenotaph built in 1899 in honour of Maharaja Jaswant Singh II. Crafted from intricately carved sheets of white marble so thin they glow amber when sunlight passes through them, it's earned the nickname the 'Taj Mahal of Marwar'.</p>
<p>Set beside a small lake with the fort towering behind, its gardens and gazebos make it one of the most peaceful and beautiful spots in Jodhpur — a gentle counterpoint to the mighty fortress above.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The glowing translucent marble in the main cenotaph.</li><li>The lakeside setting with Mehrangarh as a backdrop.</li><li>The portraits of the Marwar rulers inside.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It sits just below Mehrangarh — the two are almost always visited together. Calm, uncrowded and lovely in the morning light.</p>""")

P(slug="jodhpur-clock-tower-market", city="Jodhpur", region="Marwar", cat="Heritage Site",
  name="Clock Tower & Sardar Market", query="Ghanta Ghar Jodhpur clock tower",
  excerpt="The bustling heart of the old Blue City — a landmark clock tower ringed by a labyrinthine bazaar of spices, textiles and life.",
  tags=["Jodhpur","market","bazaar","local life"],
  info=dict(timings="Market roughly 9 AM – 9 PM (some shops closed midday)", entry="Free",
            best="Morning for the market buzz; evening for atmosphere", duration="1–2 hours", reach="Old City centre, below Mehrangarh"),
  body="""<p>At the centre of Jodhpur's old walled city stands the Ghanta Ghar, a distinctive clock tower built by Maharaja Sardar Singh — and around it swirls the Sardar Market, one of the most vibrant bazaars in Rajasthan. This is where you feel the real pulse of the Blue City.</p>
<p>Narrow lanes radiate out into a maze of stalls selling spices, textiles, silver, handicrafts, sweets and the famous local savouries. It's chaotic, colourful and endlessly photogenic — the blue-washed houses climbing toward the fort above framing every scene.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The spice and textile stalls around the market.</li><li>Wandering the blue-painted back lanes of the old city.</li><li>Local snacks — Jodhpur is famous for its street food and sweets.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It's a working market, not a tourist set-piece — bargain politely and mind your belongings in the crowds. Best combined with the walk up to Mehrangarh.</p>""")

P(slug="mandore-gardens-jodhpur", city="Jodhpur", region="Marwar", cat="Garden & Park",
  name="Mandore Gardens", query="Mandore Gardens Jodhpur",
  excerpt="The ancient former capital of Marwar — leafy gardens scattered with towering royal cenotaphs and a hall of heroes.",
  tags=["Jodhpur","garden","heritage","cenotaphs"],
  info=dict(timings="8 AM – 6 PM (daily)", entry="Free",
            best="Morning or late afternoon", duration="1–1.5 hours", reach="~9 km north of Jodhpur"),
  body="""<p>Before Jodhpur, there was Mandore — the ancient capital of the Marwar region, now a green garden complex on the city's northern edge. Shaded by trees and alive with monkeys and birds, it's a relaxed, atmospheric escape from the busy old city.</p>
<p>The gardens are famous for their devals — soaring, temple-like royal cenotaphs built in a distinctive dark stone, quite unlike the domed chhatris found elsewhere in Rajasthan. The 'Hall of Heroes', with its brightly painted figures of folk deities carved from rock, adds to the site's character.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The towering temple-style royal cenotaphs (devals).</li><li>The Hall of Heroes and its painted rock-cut figures.</li><li>The peaceful, tree-shaded gardens.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Watch for monkeys around the gardens. It's a pleasant, uncrowded half-day option away from Jodhpur's main sights.</p>""")

# ---- JAISALMER ----

P(slug="jaisalmer-fort", city="Jaisalmer", region="Thar", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Jaisalmer Fort (Sonar Quila)", query="Jaisalmer Fort",
  excerpt="A golden sandstone fortress rising from the Thar Desert — and one of the world's few 'living forts', still full of homes and life.",
  tags=["fort","Jaisalmer","UNESCO","living fort"],
  info=dict(timings="Fort open all day; palace museum ~9 AM – 6 PM", entry="Free to enter the fort; palace museum approx ₹50 (Indian) / ₹250 (foreign)",
            best="Sunrise or sunset, when the stone turns gold", duration="Half day", reach="Rises above Jaisalmer town centre — walkable"),
  body="""<p>Rising from the desert like a giant sandcastle, Jaisalmer Fort — the Sonar Quila, or Golden Fort — glows honey-gold at dawn and dusk. Built in 1156, it's one of the largest fully preserved fortified cities in the world, and remarkably, one of the very few 'living forts': a quarter of the old city's population still lives inside its walls.</p>
<p>Wandering its lanes, you pass Jain temples, carved havelis, shops, guesthouses and homes, all within the massive ramparts. The Raj Mahal (palace) museum and the fort's bastions offer views over the golden town and the endless desert beyond.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The fort glowing gold at sunrise and sunset.</li><li>The intricately carved Jain temples inside.</li><li>The views from the ramparts over the desert town.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>As a living fort, it faces conservation pressures — tread lightly and support responsible businesses. Getting lost in its lanes is part of the magic.</p>""")

P(slug="patwon-ki-haveli-jaisalmer", city="Jaisalmer", region="Thar", cat="Heritage Site",
  name="Patwon Ki Haveli", query="Patwon ki Haveli Jaisalmer",
  excerpt="The grandest of Jaisalmer's merchant mansions — a cluster of five havelis dripping with the finest golden-stone carving.",
  tags=["Jaisalmer","haveli","architecture","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="9 AM – 6 PM (daily)", entry="Approx ₹50–₹100 depending on section",
            best="Morning light on the façade", duration="1 hour", reach="In the old town, below the fort"),
  body="""<p>Jaisalmer grew rich on the desert trade routes, and its wealthy merchants poured their fortunes into extraordinary mansions. The finest of them all is Patwon Ki Haveli — actually a cluster of five interconnected havelis built in the early 19th century, and the most elaborate in the city.</p>
<p>Every surface of the golden sandstone façade is carved into lace-like screens (jharokhas), balconies and arches of astonishing delicacy. Inside, some sections are preserved as museums, revealing the opulent lifestyle of the trading families who built them.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The intricately carved five-storey façade.</li><li>The preserved interiors and their period furnishings.</li><li>The rooftop views over the old city and fort.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The lanes here are narrow — the façade is best appreciated from the small square in front. Nearby Nathmal Ji and Salim Singh havelis are also worth a look.</p>""")

P(slug="sam-sand-dunes-jaisalmer", city="Jaisalmer", region="Thar", cat="Desert",
  name="Sam Sand Dunes", query="Sam Sand Dunes Jaisalmer",
  excerpt="The classic Thar Desert experience — rolling golden dunes, camel safaris, desert camps and unforgettable sunsets.",
  tags=["desert","Jaisalmer","camel safari","camping"],
  info=dict(timings="Best late afternoon to sunset; overnight camps available", entry="Free to access; safaris & camps are packages",
            best="Sunset; October–March for cool weather", duration="Half day to overnight", reach="~40 km west of Jaisalmer toward the border"),
  body="""<p>For most travellers, the Thar Desert means Sam — a sea of rolling golden dunes about 40 km from Jaisalmer, and the setting for the quintessential Rajasthan desert experience. As the afternoon cools, camel and jeep safaris head out across the sand toward the sunset.</p>
<p>Come evening, the desert camps light up with folk music, Kalbeliya dancers, bonfires and traditional dinners under a sky thick with stars. Spending a night here — in anything from a basic tent to a luxury 'glamping' camp — is a highlight of any Rajasthan trip.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>A camel safari over the dunes at sunset.</li><li>An overnight desert camp with folk music and dance.</li><li>The star-filled night sky, far from city lights.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Choose a reputable, responsible camp and safari operator. It gets busy at peak season, so book ahead; Khuri dunes are a quieter alternative. Winter nights are cold — pack layers.</p>""")

P(slug="gadisar-lake-jaisalmer", city="Jaisalmer", region="Thar", cat="Lake & Ghat",
  name="Gadisar Lake", query="Gadisar Lake Jaisalmer",
  excerpt="A tranquil man-made oasis on the edge of the Golden City — ringed by shrines and ghats, and lovely at sunrise.",
  tags=["Jaisalmer","lake","sunrise","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="Open all day; boating during daylight", entry="Free; boating charges apply",
            best="Sunrise, for the light and birdlife", duration="45 minutes – 1 hour", reach="Just outside the old town of Jaisalmer"),
  body="""<p>Once the sole water source for the desert city of Jaisalmer, Gadisar Lake is a man-made reservoir that has become one of the town's most peaceful spots. Ringed by small temples, shrines and ghats, and entered through a beautifully carved golden-stone archway, it's an oasis in the arid landscape.</p>
<p>At sunrise the lake is at its best — soft light on the golden shrines, migratory birds on the water in winter, and boats drifting across the calm surface. It's a serene way to bookend the intensity of the fort and desert.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The ornate Tilon-ki-Pol gateway at the entrance.</li><li>Sunrise over the lake and its shrines.</li><li>A gentle paddle-boat ride and winter birdwatching.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Early morning is the ideal time — quiet, cool and beautifully lit. A calm contrast to the busy fort lanes nearby.</p>""")

P(slug="kuldhara-abandoned-village", city="Kuldhara", region="Thar", cat="Heritage Site",
  name="Kuldhara Abandoned Village", query="Kuldhara Jaisalmer",
  excerpt="A hauntingly deserted 19th-century village in the desert — abandoned overnight, and steeped in legend.",
  tags=["Jaisalmer","offbeat","history","desert"],
  info=dict(timings="8 AM – 6 PM (daily)", entry="Approx ₹10–₹100 (vehicle/entry charges)",
            best="Late afternoon", duration="1 hour", reach="~18 km south-west of Jaisalmer"),
  body="""<p>In the desert near Jaisalmer lies an eerie sight: the ruins of Kuldhara, a village said to have been abandoned overnight around two centuries ago by its Paliwal Brahmin community, who vanished en masse rather than submit to a tyrannical minister — leaving behind, so the legend goes, a curse that the village would never be resettled.</p>
<p>Today its roofless stone houses, empty lanes and a restored temple stand silent against the desert, an atmospheric and slightly haunting place to explore. Whatever the truth behind the legend, the ghost village is a compelling, offbeat detour.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>Wandering the deserted stone streets and houses.</li><li>The restored village temple.</li><li>The stark desert setting, especially near sunset.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It's often combined with a trip out to the Sam dunes. There's little shade — bring water and a hat. The atmosphere is best in the golden late-afternoon light.</p>""")
